-- U.S. Gulf Crudes Weaken as Refineries Shut Units for Maintenance
-- B y   A a r o n   C l a r k
-- 2012-01-10T18:14:34Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-10/u-s-gulf-crudes-weaken-as-refineries-shut-units-for-maintenance.html
U.S. Gulf Coast oils weakened after
refineries in Texas and  Louisiana  shut process units for planned
work, reducing demand for crude.  BP Plc (BP/)  shut a fluid catalytic cracker and an alkylation
unit for maintenance at the Texas City, Texas,  refinery , a
person with knowledge of the work said yesterday.  Valero Energy Corp. (VLO)  shut an alkylation unit at the Meraux
 refinery  in Louisiana,  Bill Day , a company spokesman in  San
Antonio , said in an e-mail today. A fluid catalytic cracker is
also shut at the plant, although not for maintenance, he said.  Light Louisiana Sweet (USCSLLSS) ’s premium to West Texas Intermediate
fell $1.25 to $10.25 a barrel at 12:18 p.m. in  New York .  Heavy
Louisiana Sweet (USCSHLSE) ’s premium dropped $2.40 to $10.60 over the U.S.
benchmark.  Thunder Horse’s premium decreased $1.70 to $10.75. Mars
Blend fell $1.45 to $7.70 over WTI.  Poseidon (USCSPOSE) ’s premium narrowed
$1.45 to $7.30 a barrel.  Southern Green Canyon (USCSSGCN)  declined $1 to $7 over WTI.  West
Texas Sour (USCSWTSM) ’s discount widened 65 cents to $2.90 a barrel.  Syncrude (USCSSYNS) ’s discount was unchanged at $2.50 below WTI.
Syncrude is a light, low-sulfur synthetic oil derived from the
 tar sands  in  Alberta .  Western Canada Select (USCSWCAS) ’s discount to WTI was unchanged at
$18.25 a barrel.  To contact the reporter on this story:
